’s Government from which countries timber with bark for firewood has been imported into the UK in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Clark of Windermere",,"Lord Clark of Windermere","HL4934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678206","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-07","<p>Her Majesty’s Revenue &amp; Customs collect and publish National Statistics for the United Kingdom on the level of imports of woodfuel under commodity code 44011000: ‘fuel wood in logs, billets, twigs, faggots or similar forms’. No record is made to differentiate the presence or absence of bark on imports of woodfuel.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for 2011-15, the latest figures for which complete data is available, are shown the Table attached.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that wood can be a pathway for the introduction and movement of harmful plant pests. That is why a new Statutory Notification Scheme for importing solid woodfuel (firewood) came into force on 1 January 2017. This requires importers bringing firewood into England and Scotland from outside the UK to provide the Forestry Commission with at least three days’ prior notification of its arrival if it is coming by sea, road or rail, and four hours’ notice if arriving by air. The Welsh Assembly Government is expected to introduce a similar regulation.</p><p> </p><p>The scheme will enable the Forestry Commission to gather information about the firewood importing trade, and to carry out risk-based and random inspections of a selection of imports. This will help to ensure that the firewood or its associated wooden packaging meets British plant health landing requirements.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL4933 ; HL4934","2017-02-07T15:07:32.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678206/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678206/answer","HL4933 HL4934  HL4935 - firewood imports with bark - Table.pdf","TABLE OF IMPORTS 2011-2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678206/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-24","Timber: Imports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact on the eco-system of importing timber with bark to the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Clark of Windermere",,"Lord Clark of Windermere","HL4935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678207","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-01","<p>As detailed in the briefing paper <em>Statistical Models and the Global Temperature Record</em> by the Chief Scientist of the Met Office, neither integrated nor linear models are consistent with a climate that is in a steady state. Further, these methods do not explicitly include any description of the physical processes affecting global temperatures and therefore have limited capability in providing information on such processes.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-01T12:37:25.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678207/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678207/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-24","Climate Change","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 12 December 2016 (HL3624), whether the criticism set out in the briefing paper <i>Statistical Models and the Global Temperature Record</i> that integrated models are "not consistent with the notion of a climate that is in a steady state" also applies to linear trend models.","false","Biography information for Lord Donoughue",,"Lord Donoughue","HL4936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678208","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-01","<p>The observed increase of global average surface temperature, increase of mean sea level and decline of snow and ice are not consistent with natural internal variability or the influence of external factors. Conversely, the observed changes are consistent with estimates of the Earth’s energy balance which show that, as a result of increasing concentrations of greenhouse gases, the Earth has absorbed more energy from incoming solar radiation than it has emitted back to space. More evidence can be found in the Working Group I contribution to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change’s Fifth Assessment Report.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-01T12:39:37.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678208/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678208/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-24","Climate Change","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what observational evidence, if any, they have of man-made climate change that is not consistent with reasonably expected natural variation.","false","Biography information for Lord Donoughue",,"Lord Donoughue","HL4937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678209","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government will provide a web service for businesses to publish information about their payment practices and performance. This will be available from April 2017 and will be part of the Gov.uk website. Small firms, suppliers, and other interested parties will be able to view the information as soon as a business publishes it. The web service is currently being developed with input from potential users to ensure it is easy to access.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-02T16:18:16.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678209/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678209/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-24","Business: Billing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps will be taken to ensure that data to be collected under the draft regulations on the duty to report on payment practices and policies will be made accessible to (1) small firms, and (2) third party intermediaries.","false","Biography information for Lord Foster of Bath",,"Lord Foster of Bath","HL4938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678210","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-02","<p>The information must be approved by a company director (or designated member of an LLP) before the large business publishes it. Suppliers using the information can raise any concerns about its accuracy with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, who will investigate. It will be a criminal offence to publish a report or information that is misleading, false or deceptive.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-02T16:18:36.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678210/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678210/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-24","Business: Billing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how the data to be provided by large firms under the draft regulations on the duty to report on payment practices and policies will be verified for accuracy.","false","Biography information for Lord Foster of Bath",,"Lord Foster of Bath","HL4939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678211","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government will provide a web service for businesses to publish information about their payment practices and performance. The reports will be available online for anyone to scrutinise.</p><p>The web service is currently being developed with input from potential users. Data collation and comparison is being investigated as part of this. We expect that collated data will be downloadable and/or available on data.gov.uk.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-02T16:17:33.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678211/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678211/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-24","Business: Billing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether data to be provided by large firms under the draft regulations on the duty to report on payment practices and policies will be collated and then published in a format which will allow for comparison between those firms.","false","Biography information for Lord Foster of Bath",,"Lord Foster of Bath","HL4940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678212","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-02","<p>Failure to publish a report as required will be a criminal offence. The company and its directors, or LLP and its designated members, will be liable. It will also be an offence to publish false or misleading information.</p><p>These offences will be punishable on summary conviction (in the Magistrates’ court) by a fine. If a concern is raised with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy that a large business might not have complied, the business will usually be contacted to remind them to comply and seek an explanation for non-compliance or discrepancies.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-02T16:16:40.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678212/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678212/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-24","Business: Billing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what will be the penalties for large firms that fail to comply with the duty to report on payment practices and policies.","false","Biography information for Lord Foster of Bath",,"Lord Foster of Bath","HL4941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678213","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Small Business Commissioner (SBC) will support small businesses to resolve payment disputes and avoid future issues by encouraging a culture change in how businesses deal with each other.</p><p>The SBC will provide general advice and information to build the confidence and capability of small business to help them assert themselves in contractual disputes and negotiate more effectively. It will also handle complaints by small suppliers about payment-related issues with their larger customers.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-02T16:16:16.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678213/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678213/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678213/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-24","Small Business Commissioner","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Small Business Commissioner’s remit will include tackling the issue of supply chain bullying<i>.</i>","false","Biography information for Lord Foster of Bath",,"Lord Foster of Bath","HL4942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678214","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-30","<p>The reciprocal rights and entitlements that will apply following the UK’s exit are subject to the wider negotiation on our future relationship with the EU and the Government has not yet begun these negotiations.</p>",,"Lord Henley","HL4944","2017-01-30T16:52:36.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678214/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678214/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678214/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-24","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what reciprocal arrangements will be put in place to guarantee, after the UK leaves the EU, the annual increase of the basic state pension for UK citizens who have retired to countries in the European Union which do not currently have reciprocal arrangements with the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL4943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678215","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-30","<p>The reciprocal rights and entitlements that will apply following the UK’s exit are subject to the wider negotiation on our future relationship with the EU and the Government has not yet begun these negotiations.</p>",,"Lord Henley","HL4943","2017-01-30T16:52:36.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678215/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678215/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-24","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the annual increase of the basic state pension for UK citizens who have retired to Spain will continue after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL4944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678216","Department of Health","false","2017-02-03","<p>Decisions related to the provision of stem cell transplantation are an operational matter for NHS England. Stem cell transplants for sickle cell disease in adults are not routinely commissioned by NHS England. Whilst stem cell transplants can be effective for some carefully selected patients, stem cell transplantation can also lead to a number of complications, some of which can be severe and life threatening.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England commissioning policy for stem cell transplants is kept under review in the light of the latest clinical evidence. The National Institute for Health Research is currently inviting research proposals for a multicentre randomised control trial to address the clinical and cost effectiveness of stem cell transplantation in adults with severe sickle cell disease. Evidence from this trial will inform NHS England commissioning policy related to stem cell transplants in adults with sickle cell disease.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-02-03T14:24:56.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678216/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678216/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-24","Sickle Cell Diseases","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why adult sufferers from sickle cell anaemia who could benefit from stem cell treatment are not able to receive such treatment under the NHS when child sufferers can; and whether they are considering changing this policy.","false","Biography information for Lord Kinnock",,"Lord Kinnock","HL4945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678217","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-01","<p>The All Party Parliamentary Group on Steel and Metal Related Industries has written to us with a copy of this report. We appreciate the time and work that has gone into this document which puts forward interesting points and recommendations. These align with the key objectives industry has asked of Government, and we have made good progress in delivering energy cost relief – paying £133m to the steel sector - EU emissions regulations, tackling the dumping of steel in the EU, reforming procurement guidelines and publishing a pipeline of procurement opportunities for the steel sector. Our goal is to work with the UK steel sector to create the right environment for investment and growth. We will continue to engage with the All Party Group as we seek to find a long-term viable solution for the industry.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-01T12:40:18.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678217/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678217/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-24","Iron and Steel: Manufacturing Industries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to respond to the report by the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Steel and Metal Related Industries <i>Steel 2020: Forging a future for the British Steel Industry</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Kinnock",,"Lord Kinnock","HL4946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678218","Home Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>Individuals who are complying with the Home Office as part of the voluntary returns process may be granted permission to rent ahead of their departure.</p><p> </p><p>People who are denied access to the private rented sector are expected to return home. Advice and support is available to help people with no right to be here return to their home countries.</p><p> </p><p>It is open to people to make temporary living arrangements which are not covered by the Right to Rent scheme ahead of their return home, in hotel accommodation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-30T16:01:40.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678218/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678218/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-24","Undocumented Migrants: Private Rented Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 9 January (HL3406), where prospective tenants who are denied access to the private rented sector under the right to rent scheme are housed pending their deportation or voluntary departure.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL4947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678219","Department of Health","false","2017-02-06","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-02-06T16:01:42.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678219/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678219/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-24","Accident and Emergency Departments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of hospital fatalities resulting from people not being admitted to accident and emergency departments since the beginning of December 2016; and what assessment they have made of whether any increase or decrease from usual numbers is a result of seasonal factors or demonstrates a long-term trend.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL4948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678220","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>Children and young people’s mental health is a priority area for this Government. We are committed to delivering the vision set out in the <em>Future in Mind</em> report, published in March 2015, which established a clear and powerful consensus about change across the whole system, including health, justice, social care and education.</p><p> </p><p>This Government will drive forward the transformation of children and young people’s mental health services to improve access and make services more widely available across the country so that where possible children can access support locally. In total the Government has made available an additional £1.4 billion over the course of this Parliament to support significant transformation in children and young people’s mental health so that there is easy access to the right support from the right service when it is needed. This includes implementing clear evidence based pathways for community-based care to avoid unnecessary admissions to inpatient care.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-02-07T13:14:10.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678220/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678220/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-24","Anxiety: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of figures recently released by NHS Digital, what action they are taking in response to the rising number of children being admitted to hospital suffering from anxiety.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL4949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678221","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-06","The Prime Minister, the Chancellor of the Exchequer and the Secretary of State for International Trade represented the Government at the 2017 Davos summit. Total verified UK Government attendance costs are not yet available. As part of the Government’s transparency agenda, total costs for Ministerial visits are published quarterly and the information requested is under preparation. It will form part of the next set of Departmental returns for the first quarter of 2017.",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-06T11:45:21.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678221/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678221/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-24","World Economic Forum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the total cost of all UK Government attendance expenses for the Davos Summit.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL4950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678222","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Government will ensure that all views can be reflected in our analysis of the options for the UK’s withdrawal from the European Union and we are going to listen and talk to as many organisations, companies and institutions as possible to do this.</p><p> </p><p>We have set up a new Joint Ministerial Committee on EU Negotiations, which brings together constituent parts of the United Kingdom to discuss issues stemming from the negotiation process which may impact upon or have consequences for the UK Government, the Scottish Government, the Welsh Government or the Northern Ireland Executive. The Committee met for the third time on 19 January.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Northern Ireland has regular meetings with the political parties in Northern Ireland to discuss the implications of the decision to exit the European Union. In addition, he established a Business Advisory Group in September to ensure that the views of the business community are reflected in the process of exiting the European Union. The Secretary of State has also had positive engagement with representatives of the voluntary and community sector.</p><p> </p><p>All these views are being taken into consideration in the process leading up to the triggering of Article 50 and the preparations for the UK’s exit from the European Union.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2017-02-07T13:19:55.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678222/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678222/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-24","Brexit: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the Supreme Court ruling in the case of <i>R (on the application of Miller and another) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union</i>, what steps they are taking to ensure that the views of all communities in Northern Ireland are taken into consideration when Article 50 is triggered.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL4951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678223","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Government remains fully and firmly committed to preserving and maintaining the Belfast Agreement, its successors and the institutions. The Government keeps in regular contact with the Irish Government on a range of issues in accordance with the well-established three stranded approach. Most recently, the Prime Minister met the Taoiseach on 30 January in Dublin.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2017-02-07T12:50:53.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678223/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678223/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-24","Belfast Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the Supreme Court ruling in the case of <i>R (on the application of Miller and another) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union</i> and of the pending elections to the Northern Ireland Assembly, what discussions they have had with the government of Ireland regarding their roles as co-guarantors under the Good Friday Agreement.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL4952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678224","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-02","<p>The 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review directed the Ministry of Defence (MOD) to reduce its civilian headcount by 30 per cent by 2020. This is Government policy and we will take an approach to this that does not diminish either our people or Defence.</p><p>We need to be sure that we are always getting maximum value for the taxpayer. Wherever possible we will rebalance our investments towards the front line - this means reshaping the MOD Civil Service workforce to focus on its core Civil Servant roles.</p><p>A central part of making the MOD Civil Service more innovative and more efficient is reorganising work so that it is done in the best place possible - by civilian, military or contractor personnel. In a number of cases, this may mean using alternative delivery models, such as outsourcing, amongst others.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-02T16:34:11.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678224/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678224/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Ministry of Defence: Civilians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they plan to reduce the number of civilian personnel employed by the Ministry of Defence from 56,430 to 41,000, as set out in the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL4953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678225","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-02","<p>The 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review committed Defence to develop a new Armed Forces offer (remunerative and non-remunerative) for new joiners from April 2019, which better meets the expectations of future recruits and targets resources on the people we need most. It will better reflect the realities of modern life and the UK's current financial position, whilst taking account of the unique demands that military service imposes on its people.</p><p>A range of major People Change Programmes are currently underway, which will collectively ensure we are well positioned for future strategic challenges. This is a challenging portfolio of projects with tight timelines for delivery and includes the New Employment Model (NEM), Future Reserves 2020 (FR20), the Defence Diversity and Inclusion Programme (DDIP) and the Armed Forces People Programme (AFPP). The AFPP comprises four projects: Future Accommodation Model (FAM); Flexible Engagements System (FES); New Joiner Offer (NJO); and, Enterprise Approach (EA).</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-02T16:32:37.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678225/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678225/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Armed Forces: Recruitment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 20 January (HL4640), what are the short- and long-term plans they have in place to ensure that the offer of military service in the armed forces continues to be competitive.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL4954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678226","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-03","<p>Joint Force 2025 will be composed of a full spectrum of capabilities, and be able to conduct a wide range of operations, up to major combat operations. At the most demanding end of the scale we will be able to deploy a potent expeditionary force of around 50,000. Deployment times would depend on the scale, expected duration and location of the commitment.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-03T14:44:56.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678226/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678226/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Armed Forces: Deployment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the length of time it would take to deploy Joint Force 2025 following authorisation of the Prime Minister, in the light of the maximum 66,000 personnel which may be deployed, as set out in <i>Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015: Defence Key Facts</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL4955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678227","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-02","<p>The UK is one of Europe's biggest military powers: we make a significant contribution to Common Security and Defence Policy SDP military operations and civilian missions; we are committed to spending 2 per cent of our GDP on Defence, with 20 per cent of that on upgrading major equipment; and we spend a further 0.7 per cent of our GNI on international development. In addition, our diplomatic, security, and intelligence services are world class, and, as a nuclear power, and one of the five permanent members of the UN Security Council, we have major global reach and influence.</p><p>The nature of our future relationship with the EU on foreign, security, and Defence issues remains under consideration. We are, however, clear that we will continue to play a leading role in European and wider global security, and wish to continue to cooperate with European partners to tackle shared challenges.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-02T16:36:58.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678227/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678227/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","EU Defence Policy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the UK's future involvement in the EU's foreign security and defence missions.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL4956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678228","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-03","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the Written Ministerial Statement made by the Secretary of State for Defence (Michael Fallon) on 30 June 2016 (HLWS50).</p><p> </p><p>The public consultation sought views on the inclusion of the revised Army Trained Strength figures within the Monthly Service Personnel Statistics publication. No external responses were received. The change was implemented from 1 October 2016.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-03T14:44:41.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678228/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678228/answer","Hansard Extract  30 June 2016 HLWS50.docx","Strategic Defence and Security Review","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678228/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Army","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to their consultation on changes to the definition of trained strength for the army, why this change has been proposed.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL4957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678229","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Veterans' Gateway is a £2 million programme run through a consortium of Combat Stress, PoppyScotland, SSAFA and Connect Assist, led by The Royal British Legion, to set up a one-stop service to better support the UK's Armed Forces Veterans community. The new service will provide a simple single point of contact through a 24/7 phone number with a professional voice at the end of the line, SMS access, a dedicated website and a mobile enabled web app to make it easier for former Service personnel to access support on a range of issues including housing, employability and health issues. Veterans in Northern Ireland, like other UK Veterans, will also be able to access the Veterans Gateway. Subject to successful trials, the Veterans' Gateway will launch in May 2017 through an event to be held on the same day in each of the home nations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-03T14:45:16.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678229/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678229/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Veterans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government on what date the new veterans gateway will become operational.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL4958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678230","Department for Education","false","2017-02-01","<p>Non-compliance with the regulations will constitute an ‘unlawful act’ and fall within the existing enforcement powers of the Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) under the Equality Act 2006.</p><p> </p><p>The EHRC can investigate an employer who it suspects of committing an unlawful act, with a view to making them put it right.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-01T15:24:51.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678230/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678230/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-24","Equal Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the introduction of mandatory gender pay gap reporting under the Equality Act 2010 (Gender Pay Gap Information) Regulations 2017 is intended to facilitate the use by the Equality and Human Rights Commission of their enforcement powers relating to the elimination of unlawful sexual discrimination in the field of employment.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678231","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-07","<p>I regret the delay in answering the Noble Lord's Question for Written Answer HL3278. An answer was given on Monday 30 January 2017.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-07T15:11:28.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678231/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678231/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-24","Ministry of Justice: Written Questions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to answer Lord Bradley's Question for Written Answer HL3278 tabled on 16 November 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL4960"
