"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677591","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-30","<p>The government recently consulted on measures to reform the whiplash claims process, and sought feedback on whether any specific measures should be put in place in relation to claims management companies (CMCs) operating in the personal injury sector. This important consultation closed on 6 January 2017. The Government has undertaken to publish its response to the consultation by 7 April.</p><p> </p><p>The government commissioned a fundamental review of the regulation of CMCs which reported in 2016. Carol Brady considered the regulation and role of CMCs and concluded that a tougher regulatory regime should be established. The government has committed to strengthening regulation further by transferring responsibility to the Financial Conduct Authority with powers to require all CMCs to be re-authorised and to hold managers of CMCs directly accountable for the actions of their businesses.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","61096 ; 61097","2017-01-30T17:31:54.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677591/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677591/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-23","Claims Management Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will assess the potential merits of banning claims management companies.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","61098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677592","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-27","<p>Information on convictions for 2016, including that for sexual offences, is planned for publication in May 2017</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-01-27T12:46:55.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677592/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677592/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-23","Sexual Offences: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the conviction rate for (a) rape and (b) sexual assault charges was in (i) Nottinghamshire and (ii) England in 2016.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","61156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677593","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-26","<p>The Government’s consultation, <em>Reforming the Soft Tissue Injury (‘whiplash’) Claims Process – A Consultation on arrangements concerning personal injury claims in England and Wales</em>, began on 17 November 2016 and closed on 6 January. The Government has undertaken to publish its response to the consultation by 7 April.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-26T16:03:33.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677593/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677593/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-23","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether she intends to undertake further consultation on reforming the soft tissue injury (whiplash) claims process.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","61125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677594","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-01","<p>Prison Rules require prisons to actively encourage prisoners to maintain outside contacts and meaningful family ties.</p><p> </p><p>Prisoners also have a statutory entitlement to send and receive letters and are entitled to one free letter to inform someone they are being transferred. They are also given the access to make a telephone call on the day of their arrival to a new prison to inform their family of their new location if they have not been able to do so in advance. It is the prisoners’ responsibility to advise their family if they are transferring to another prison.</p><p> </p><p>The prisoner can make an appeal through the complaints system and is entitled to a reply, which should provide clear reasons for their decision. If they are not satisfied with their response they can write to the Prison Ombudsman. Families can also raise any concerns directly with the Prison.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-02-01T12:18:30.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677594/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677594/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-23","Prisoners' Transfers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether it is her Department's policy to provide information to prisoners and their families in the event of their transfer to another prison; and by what mechanism prisoners and their families can appeal a prison transfer.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","61225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677595","Prime Minister","false","2017-01-31","<p>A reply will be sent in due course.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-01-31T16:51:36.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677595/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677595/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677595/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-23","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she has received a copy of the Birmingham Students' Brexit Manifesto; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","61181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677596","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-27","<p>Arrangements for the towage of decommissioned oil and gas infrastructure, and the routes they may take, are commercial decisions and government does not collect data to allow for a meaningful forward estimate to be made.</p><p> </p><p>Those managing such operations will need to comply with national and international conventions and regulations applying to shipping and the decommissioning of oil and gas infrastructure.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-27T11:33:51.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677596/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677596/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677596/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Offshore Industry: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the amount of (a) dry and (b) wet towage of decommissioned oil and gas infrastructure that will use (i) Western and Northern Isles and (ii) Pentland Firth sea lanes in each year from 2017-18 to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","61182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677597","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-27","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency does not conduct surveys on internationally registered merchant vessels. The UK, under the requirement of EU Directive 2009/16, undertakes port-State Control inspections on internationally registered vessels in UK waters.</p><p> </p><p>The number of qualified Port State Control (PSC) inspectors in each of the calendar years was as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>PSC Inspectors</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>89</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>103</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>91</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>92</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>85</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>59</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>66</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-27T11:54:41.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677597/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677597/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Merchant Shipping: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many employees of the Maritime and Coastguard Agency were qualified to inspect or survey internationally registered merchant vessels over 500 gross tonnage for compliance with international maritime safety regulations in each year from 2010-11 to 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","61203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677598","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-27","<p>Inspections of internationally registered merchant vessels are carried out on any vessel to which one or more international Conventions applies. It should be noted that some of the international conventions do, however, have lower limits than a gross tonnage of 500, and some have different criteria than tonnage.</p><p> </p><p>The number of inspections are recorded on calendar year basis and the following table shows the number of inspections carried out in the years 2010‑2016:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Inspections</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>1832</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>1604</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>1543</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1540</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>1456</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>1123</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-27T11:41:14.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677598/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677598/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Merchant Shipping: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many inspections or surveys of internationally registered merchant vessels over 500 gross tonnes were conducted by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency  in each year from 2010-11 to 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","61183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677599","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-31","<p>The number of vessels detained for infringement of one or more of the three Conventions listed above was (i) 43 in 2015 and (ii) 50 in 2016. The attached table lists those vessels and their IMO number.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-31T12:12:31.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677599/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677599/answer","061179 - Table Vessels detained in 2015 and 2016.docx","UIN 61179 - Table of vessels detained 2015 & 2016","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677599/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Merchant Shipping: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which internationally registered vessels were detained by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency for infringement of the (a) Maritime Labour, (b) Safety of Life at Sea and (c) Standards in Training, Certification and Watchkeeping conventions in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","61179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677600","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-27","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) has provided in-house training for 152 Marine Surveyors since 2010. This is provided by MCA experts on the Maritime Labour Convention (MLC), 2006 and its enforcement. Some Marine Surveyors have also attended international training courses on matters relating to the International Labour Organisation and the Paris Memorandum of Understanding on Port State Control.</p><p> </p><p>All new Marine Surveyors are given training on the MLC, 2006 as part of their induction process.</p><p> </p><p>The MCA is not responsible for enforcement of the MLC, 2006 in Red Ensign Group ports.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-27T11:16:31.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677600/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677600/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Merchant Shipping: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what training Maritime and Coastguard Agency staff receive on the enforcement of the Maritime Labour Convention on internationally registered merchant vessels working from (a) UK and (b) Red Ensign Group ports.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","61180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677601","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-26","<p>Smart Motorways are at the core of Highways England’s £15bn investment programme to transform England’s Strategic Road Network, helping to ease congestion and improve traffic flow. Keeping traffic moving reduces stop-start decelerations and accelerations, which in itself has air quality benefits.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England will announce any measures to improve air quality on the M1 between junctions 32-35a when the Smart Motorway scheme opens, which is expected to be in March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England has undertaken environmental assessments of the scheme during the design and construction. These are available on Highways England’s website.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","61159 ; 61237 ; 61251","2017-01-26T16:03:53.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677601/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677601/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","M1: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what mitigation measures his Department has assessed for the purposes of nitrogen dioxide and particulate pollution reduction between junctions 33 and 34 on the M1; and of those measures which have been assessed as viable and are under consideration for implementation.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","61236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677602","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-26","<p>Smart Motorways are at the core of Highways England’s £15bn investment programme to transform England’s Strategic Road Network, helping to ease congestion and improve traffic flow. Keeping traffic moving reduces stop-start decelerations and accelerations, which in itself has air quality benefits.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England will announce any measures to improve air quality on the M1 between junctions 32-35a when the Smart Motorway scheme opens, which is expected to be in March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England has undertaken environmental assessments of the scheme during the design and construction. These are available on Highways England’s website.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","61159 ; 61236 ; 61251","2017-01-26T16:03:53.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677602/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677602/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","M1","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the Smart Motorway between junctions 32 and 35a of the M1 is due to open; and whether any speed limits are to be imposed on that section of the M1.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","61237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677603","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-26","<p>Smart Motorways are at the core of Highways England’s £15bn investment programme to transform England’s Strategic Road Network, helping to ease congestion and improve traffic flow. Keeping traffic moving reduces stop-start decelerations and accelerations, which in itself has air quality benefits.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England will announce any measures to improve air quality on the M1 between junctions 32-35a when the Smart Motorway scheme opens, which is expected to be in March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England has undertaken environmental assessments of the scheme during the design and construction. These are available on Highways England’s website.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","61236 ; 61237 ; 61251","2017-01-26T16:03:53.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677603/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677603/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677603/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","M1: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of levels of (a) nitrogen dioxide, (b) particulate and (c) other pollution between junctions 33 and 34 of the M1 motorway; what he plans those levels to be at that location once the M1 becomes a Smart motorway there; and what estimate he has made of the potential for reduction in those levels from planned mitigation measures.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","61159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677604","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-26","<p>I am not aware of any representations or discussions with myself or my Department on the number 30 bus service in Hemsworth.</p><p> </p><p>However, where a commercial bus operator decides to discontinue a particular service, it is open to the local authority to decide to support that service itself and to invite other bus operators to tender to run that service in future. My department devolves over £2 million of funding to West Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive each year under the Bus Service Operators Grant system, which can be used by the authority to support bus services, including those which are under threat of closure.</p><p> </p><p>I understand that the West Yorkshire Combined Authority has now decided to support this service itself, and that the number 30 will continue but run by another operator.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-26T13:38:03.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677604/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677604/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what (a) representations he has received and (b) discussions he has had with the relevant local authority on support or extra funding for people affected by closure of the number 30 bus route in Hemsworth constituency; and what provision his Department makes available for (i) people and (ii) local communities affected by the discontinuance of (A) rural or (B) other local bus fare provision.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","61160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677605","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-27","<p>Officials from the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) have been in continued contact with both the company, GOL, which has employed the crew and the Indian Maritime Administration (DGS-Directorate General of Shipping), the flag‑State, to try to resolve the situation regarding both (a) outstanding wages being paid in full and (b) that seafarers do not incur cost of repatriation.</p><p> </p><p>The MCA understand that the DGS are also in contact with GOL. The MCA is putting as much pressure as they can to try and resolve the situation and get the wages paid. The only power available to the MCA is detaining the ship.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-27T11:12:31.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677605/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677605/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677605/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Merchant Shipping: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Maritime and Coastguard Agency's press release of 18 January 2017, Foreign flagged ships under detention in the UK during December 2016, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that seafarers on the Malaviya Seven (a) are paid the wages owed in full and (b) do not incur costs from repatriation.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","61178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677606","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-26","<p>The Department for Transport and Civil Aviation Authority are in continuous dialogue with European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) in the regular course of their business. The UK has been, and is, an active and influential EASA member and UK expertise has contributed significantly to the high standards of aviation safety in Europe. It is the Government’s intention to maintain consistently high standards of aviation safety once we have left the EU.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-26T16:11:56.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677606/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677606/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677606/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Aviation: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when officials from his Department last met officials from the European Aviation Safety Agency to discuss the implications for aviation safety as a result of the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","61120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677607","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-31","<p>The Hyperloop One Global Challenge is a privately-run competition, so it would not be appropriate for government to provide support for individual entries. The Department for Transport’s Science Advisory Council will publish a paper on hyperloop shortly setting out its view of the technical credibility of the concept and the opportunities it offers to UK industry.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-31T13:28:22.47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677607/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677607/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677607/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Public Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what support his Department has given to the four British bids to build Hyperloop lines in the UK; and what steps his Department has taken to assess the potential merits of Hyperloop lines.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","61105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677608","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-26","<p>Ministers and officials have regular meetings with representatives of Transport for London at which various subjects are discussed, including pedicabs. The Department has been working closely with Transport for London on proposals for legislation to enable the Mayor of London to regulate the pedicab trade.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-26T16:31:17.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677608/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677608/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Pedicabs: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with Transport for London on regulation of pedicabs.","false","Biography information for Mark Field","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","61241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677609","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-26","<p>The Department for Transport has received representations from a number of businesses located in the West End of London who are concerned about the impacts of pedicabs on their customers, mainly in respect of congestion and anti-social behaviour. We are working with Transport for London to develop legislation to allow the Mayor of London to regulate the pedicab trade.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-26T16:34:47.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677609/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677609/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Pedicabs: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of unlicensed pedicabs on London's reputation as a tourist destination.","false","Biography information for Mark Field","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","61242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677610","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-26","<p>Smart Motorways are at the core of Highways England’s £15bn investment programme to transform England’s Strategic Road Network, helping to ease congestion and improve traffic flow. Keeping traffic moving reduces stop-start decelerations and accelerations, which in itself has air quality benefits.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England will announce any measures to improve air quality on the M1 between junctions 32-35a when the Smart Motorway scheme opens, which is expected to be in March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England has undertaken environmental assessments of the scheme during the design and construction. These are available on Highways England’s website.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","61159 ; 61236 ; 61237","2017-01-26T16:03:53.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677610/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677610/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677610/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","M1: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to reduce nitrogen dioxide and particulate pollution levels between junctions 33 and 34 of the M1 to the level set down as acceptable in relevant EU directives; and over what timescale he plans to make those reductions.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","61251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677611","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-27","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) will work with the ship’s owner and the flag-State to ensure the welfare of the crew when an internationally registered ship is detained in a UK port.</p><p> </p><p>The MCA also works closely with local welfare bodies, such as the Merchant Navy Welfare Board, the Mission to Seafarers and the Apostleship of the Sea, who also provide assistance to the seafarers.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-27T11:58:45.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677611/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677611/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Merchant Shipping: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Maritime and Coastguard Agency's (MCA) press release of 18 January 2017, what the process is for ensuring the welfare of seafarers working on internationally registered merchant ships detained in UK ports by the MCA for breaches of international maritime regulations.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","61274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677612","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-27","<p>In response to the Maritime Growth Study the Government has been taking action to put the UK Ship Register on a more commercial footing. Progress to put in place appropriate resource and infrastructure to commercialise the UKSR is already being demonstrated.</p><p> </p><p>In January 2017 Michael Parker was appointed as the Maritime and Coastguard Agency’s (MCA’s) first Non-Executive Chairman. In addition, Doug Barrow has also been appointed as the Director for the UK Ship Register and will take up the post in April 2017. Both these appointments will play a leading role in shaping the future transformation of the UKSR and championing the UK Flag.</p><p> </p><p>Simultaneously, the MCA is working on a number of reforms to improve the quality of its services as part of a wider commitment to generate growth in the maritime sector, encourage greater investment in the UK and promote the UK flag as a world-class register that attracts quality ship owners.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport will continue to work closely with the MCA, in particular the new Non-Executive Chairman and new Director of the UKSR as it explores options for future reforms of the UK Ship register.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-27T12:11:11.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677612/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677612/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-23","Shipping: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to bring forward proposals to reform the UK Shipping Register.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","61288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677613","Wales Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Wales Office holds absence data from 1 April 2011. Fewer than five civil servants were on a leave of absence from work in the Wales Office due to mental illness in any month from this date. A full answer would risk the identification of individuals and is therefore not provided.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-01-30T12:14:44.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677613/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677613/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-01-23","Wales Office: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many civil servants in his Department were on a leave of absence from work due to mental illness in each month of the year since January 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","61201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677614","Women and Equalities","false","2017-01-31","<p>The Government Equalities Office has approximately 50 staff members, and therefore a small number of Senior Civil Servants. To avoid the possibility of individuals being identified, we are unable to release the data requested.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-31T17:44:27.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677614/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677614/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-01-23","Government Equalities Office: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many senior civil servants in her Department were on a leave of absence from work due to mental illness in each month of the year since January 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","61202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677615","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>DWP does not see any reason why Discretionary Housing Payments cannot be paid to Universal Credit claimants who have Managed Payments to their Landlord in place.</p><p> </p><p>However, if a Local Authority decides not to accept an application for DHP on the grounds that a managed payment to the landlord is in place, guidance is clear that DWP can, in agreement with the claimant, remove that arrangement to allow the application to be made.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-31T14:51:22.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677615/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677615/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reason the universal credit regulations require that a claimant with a managed payment to landlord (MPtL) is unable to apply for a discretionary housing payment from their local authority while a MPtL is in place.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","61190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677616","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-27","<p>‘Improving Lives’, the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper, published in October 2016, sets out our intention to remove the long-standing injustices and barriers that stop disabled people and people with health conditions from getting into work, staying in work and getting on. Through the Green Paper we are asking about the barriers preventing employers from recruiting and retaining disabled people and people with health conditions, and what measures would help them in doing so.</p><p>We are also reforming and expanding Government schemes that support employers and employees with health and disability issues. For example, through Access to Work and Disability Confident. Access to Work provides practical and financial support with the additional costs faced by individuals whose health or disability affects the way they do their job.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-27T13:40:47.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677616/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677616/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government is taking to ensure disabled people have the right support in place to stay in work.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","61194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677617","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>This information is not currently available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-31T16:57:59.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677617/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677617/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Universal Credit: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit claimants currently have a managed payment to landlord in each London borough.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","61189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677618","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>As of December 2016, the number of people claiming Universal Credit in Tower Hamlets, including both those in and not in receipt of a payment, was 2,000</p><p> </p><p>This information is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a>.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-31T14:46:21.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677618/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677618/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Universal Credit: Tower Hamlets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants are in receipt of universal credit in Tower Hamlets.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","61172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677619","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-26","<p>Customers are usually assigned to their nearest Jobcentre according to their postcode when making a claim, however claimants can elect to change the Jobcentre they attend.</p><p> </p><p>Where we are proposing changes to our estate we have provided details of the future locations of our sites so that our claimants can understand the impact on their travel arrangements.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-26T15:47:01.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677619/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677619/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 19 January 2017 to Question 60016, what criteria are used to allocate claimants to a particular jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","61176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677620","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-26","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-01-26T08:36:32.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677620/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677620/answer","PQ 61153.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Average Salary Men/Women","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677620/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-23","Pay: Ashfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the average salary for (a) men and (b) women in Ashfield constituency was in each year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","61153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677621","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-26","<p>The information requested is not currently available. The Department updated its strategy for releasing official statistics on Universal Credit (UC) in December 2016. As outlined in the strategy, officials are currently assessing the data for UC and will only release information once the necessary quality assurance work has taken place. These statistics will be published in accordance with the relevant protocols in the Code of Practice for official statistics.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit official statistics and the Departments release strategy can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-26T15:38:30.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677621/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677621/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Universal Credit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in Scotland received the carer element of universal credit in each of the last two years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","61149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677622","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-26","<p>This information is not currently available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-26T15:43:05.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677622/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677622/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Universal Credit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of universal credit awards in Scotland are made under split payment arrangements.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","61151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677623","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>A range of financial support is offered as part of the Universal Support framework which is delivered by jobcentres and local partners, such as Local Authorities, to help claimants manage their claim or award of Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>The department also works with the financial industry to develop products to support claimants.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-31T14:43:18.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677623/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677623/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what new financial savings products have been introduced by third party companies to support people in receipt of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","61161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677624","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-26","<p>The criteria for equality analysis requires us to pay due regard to the requirements of the Equality Act 2010 and enables us to consider equality as part of our decision making processes. We are legally required to consider the equality impacts of policies and processes on people who share protected characteristics and provide evidence that this has been taken into account. This helps us comply with our Public Sector Equality Duty as part of the Equality Act 2010, which covers the protected characteristics of:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Age</li><li>Disability</li><li>Gender reassignment</li><li>Pregnancy and maternity</li><li>Race</li><li>Religion or belief</li><li>Sex</li><li>Sexual orientation</li><li>Marriage and civil partnership - in respect of eliminating unlawful discrimination only.</li></ul><p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for service reconfiguration. This will include feedback from public consultation in those locations where this applies.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-26T15:28:13.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677624/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677624/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the criteria are for the equality analysis being carried out on the use of Anniesland Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","61107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677625","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-27","<p>We started a consultation process for the proposed closure of some Glasgow Jobcentres on 7 December 2016 and we will continue to collect feedback from people until the consultation closes on 31 January 2017.</p><p> </p><p>We have also received a number of questions from MPs, MSPs and other representatives.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-27T13:10:52.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677625/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677625/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Jobcentres: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what representations his Department has received on the future leasing of job centre offices in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","61081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677626","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>Guidance to work coaches makes it clear that conditionality requirements must always be reasonable, taking into account individual personal circumstances. There is specific guidance on the internal DWP intranet for Jobseekers Allowance, Employment and Support Allowance and Universal Credit covering the consideration, referral and application of a sanction for a vulnerable claimant.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-31T14:39:44.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677626/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677626/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance is provided to staff of his Department on the application of sanctions to vulnerable claimants.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","61082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677627","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-26","<p>In nominal terms, we expect to spend more in 2018/19 than in 2017/18 (£120,084M in 2017/18 compared with £121,870M in 2018/19). However, when adjusted for inflation (i.e. in real-terms), the Department will be spending slightly less on pensioner benefits in 2018/19 than in 2017/18 (2016/17 prices: £118,365M in 2017/18 compared with £117,632M in 2018/19 – 0.6% less).</p><p> </p><p>This is because of rising State Pension age for women during that period which means that fewer women are moving from working age to become eligible for State Pension and other pensioner benefits. This also affects some men, as some benefits, such as Pension Credit, have eligibility age linked to female State Pension age. As a result, the number of people claiming pensioner benefits is forecast to be slightly lower in 2018/19 compared to 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p>Once the rise in State Pension age to 66 is complete in October 2020, increasing longevity means that the number people over State Pension age is projected to grow, resulting in a corresponding growth in forecast real-terms pensioner benefit expenditure.</p><p> </p><p>The Pension Act 2014, section 27, commits the Government to a structured review of State Pension age every 6 years to ensure that the costs of increasing longevity are shared fairly between the generations, and to provide greater clarity around how State Pension age will change in the future. The first Government review of State Pension age is underway and will be published before 7 May 2017.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-26T15:35:40.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677627/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677627/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Pensioners: Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons his Department plans to spend less on pensions and pensioner benefits in 2018-19 than in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","61134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677628","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-26","<p>The Department has not made any assessment of the amount of time GP practice staff spend compiling evidence for patients making claims for Personal Independence Payment (PIP). GPs are only required to provide clinical information and not to make an assessment of their patient’s PIP claim as this is the role of the Department’s Case Manager.</p><p>If a healthcare professional working on behalf of the Department requires clinical information from a GP they will request it directly from the GP and the GP is able to claim a fee. If a claimant requests a reconsideration of their claim, the Case Manager may ask the claimant if they have any additional evidence, which may include medical evidence to support their claim. A claimant may choose to ask their GP for evidence at this stage or at an appeal stage if they feel it supports their claim.</p><p> </p><p>In the Improving Lives Green Paper, we are currently consulting on the sharing of data between the two assessments for Employment Support Allowance/ Universal Credit and PIP. We are also exploring how the assessment process could use data already gathered by the NHS or local authority to ensure people do not have to provide the same information.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-26T16:51:15.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677628/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677628/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Atos Healthcare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department has made an assessment of the amount of time GP practices' staff spend compiling correct evidence for the proper assessment of their patients' personal independence payment claims due to inaccuracies in Atos reports; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","61280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677629","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-26","<p>GPs are paid a prearranged fee of £33.50 by assessment providers for each completed further evidence request, as the information requested is not included in their contractual agreement.</p><p>The Department does not prescribe GPs with criteria on how they should handle these requests. That is purely a decision for the GP surgery.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-26T15:51:54.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677629/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677629/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Atos Healthcare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether Atos reimburses GP practices for any costs incurred when GPs have employed a staff member to deal with the administration of requests relating to personal independence payment claims.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","61277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677630","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-26","<p>Atos does not send reports to GPs but it does send requests for medical information which is intended for use to support the assessment process. The GP details used by Atos for correspondence purposes are provided to them by the claimant.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-26T15:55:05.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677630/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677630/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Atos Healthcare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what quality assurance systems Atos has in place to minimise the number of reports wrongly sent to GP practices that do not relate to patients within those practices.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","61278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677631","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-26","<p>We have consulted and engaged widely, and continue to do so, with disabled people, carers and representative organisations to ensure the claiming process for PIP works smoothly and efficiently for all claimants, regardless of their condition or disability. In addition we have recently undertaken research with a range of PIP claimants examining their experiences of the PIP claims process. The results from this research are being analysed and will be published in due course<strong>.</strong></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-26T15:58:31.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677631/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677631/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential effect of the claims process on the physical and mental health of personal independence payment claimants.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","61279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677632","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>Motability is an independent charitable organisation and it would not be appropriate to publish communications between Motability and the Department that were sent in confidence.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-31T12:24:41.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677632/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677632/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Motability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will place in the Library the written correspondence between his Department and Motability from the last three months on possible changes to the Motability scheme.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","61224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677633","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-30","<p>This information is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-30T17:24:58.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677633/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677633/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Social Security Benefits: Early Retirement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the annual cost to the public purse of administering working age benefits to people who have retired on health grounds but not yet reached pensionable age.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","61227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677634","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-31","<p>The Department continues to work closely with Motability and other Departments to explore ways to better support disabled people, including those PIP claimants who are not in receipt of the enhanced-rate mobility component of PIP. We have had a range of discussions on this issue.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-31T12:29:00.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677634/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677634/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-23","Personal Independence Payment: Motability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions his Department has had with (a) other Departments and (b) Motability on extending the Motability scheme to personal independence payment claimants not receiving the highest rate of mobility support; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","61226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677635","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-26","<p>The British Business Bank is supporting £625.1m of finance to 2,632 SMEs in the West Midlands region. These figures exclude Start-up Loans, which have supported 3,820 West Midlands businesses (with £23.4m of finance) since inception in 2012.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-26T14:21:30.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677635/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677635/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Small Businesses: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 20 January 2017 to Question 60473, what estimate he has made of the number of businesses in the West Midlands in receipt of funding from the British Business Bank; what the value of that funding is; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","61248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677636","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-26","The Government is carefully considering the recommendations of the Competition and Market Authority report on the energy sector, and will be setting out its response in due course.","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-26T17:23:24.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677636/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677636/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government plans to bring forward legislative proposals to require energy companies to give the lowest tariff to their customers.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","61220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677637","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-26","<table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Funding</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>£932,000 (actual spend)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>£697,631 (actual spend)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>£551,461 (actual spend)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>£532,032*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>Not available **</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>£500,000*</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>* This is the budget allocated for these financial years, as actual spend is not available.</p><p> </p><p>**The Employment Agency Standards budget was held at a higher level of aggregation and managed across a number of different programmes, so we are unable to provide a figure for that financial year.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-26T14:19:46.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677637/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677637/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Employment Agency Standards Inspectorate: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the budget of the Employment Agency Standards Inspectorate has been in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","61285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677638","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-26","<p>In the Autumn Statement, my rt. hon. Friend the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced regional Growth Deal awards worth £1.8 billion across England. Individual awards for Northern Powerhouse Local Enterprise Partnerships were announced on 23 January. We plan to announce all remaining Local Enterprise Partnership Growth Deal awards over the coming weeks.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-26T10:46:01.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677638/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677638/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Local Growth Deals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the Northern Powerhouse Growth Deal allocations announced on 23 January 2017, if he will publish similar information relating to each Growth Deal allocation made under the Autumn Statement 2016 for each local enterprise partnership in other parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","61250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677639","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-26","<p>Policy development is under way for small modular reactors. Phase One of the competition remains open, and plans for the future of the competition will be shared with the House in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-26T17:00:48.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677639/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677639/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Nuclear Reactors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will publish a road map for the development of small nuclear reactors.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","61276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677640","Department for Education","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Department for Education supports adult further education and skills training through the Adult Education Budget. Since 2011 Colleges and training providers have the flexibility to determine how they use their budget allocation, working with Local Enterprise Partnerships and local commissioners to determine the offer that best meets local needs. This approach enables providers to deliver learning in locations and at times that suit their learners. There is no requirement for Colleges to report on the times at which they make courses available, and we have not conducted a central assessment.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-02-07T14:05:54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677640/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677640/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-23","Adult Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of changes in the level of provision of adult education courses available in the evening since 2010; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","61136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677641","Department for Education","false","2017-01-27","<p>We are helping unemployed people of all ages to obtain employment by equipping them with the skills that employers need.</p><p>The Adult Education Budget helps young people aged 19-23 who need a second chance to achieve the qualifications they did not achieve in school (English and maths) and the unemployed who are looking to gain the skills needed to enter and progress in work.</p><p>We offer Traineeships, an education and training programme involving work placements, which aim to help unemployed young people prepare for an apprenticeship, other sustainable employment or further training.</p><p>The number of adults (19+) achieving a level 4+ qualification is 14,100 and has increased since last year (11,400). The Government has set out in the Industrial Strategy Green Paper how, building on the Skills Plan, it intends to grow advanced technical education.</p><p>We are committed to ensuring we have a strong skills system that can drive increases in productivity, improvements in social mobility and help make a success of Brexit.</p><p>New employer-led apprenticeship standards are now delivering the skills that employers need at all levels and we are rolling out more higher and degree apprenticeships.</p><p>We are also radically reforming technical education, creating a simplified, high status system consisting of 15 occupational routes encompassing all technical education.</p><p>To support this provision we are investing in specialist institutions - as announced in the Industrial Strategy Green Paper (published 23 January), the Government has made available £170m capital funding for new Institutes of Technology to deliver higher Technical Education in STEM subjects at higher skills levels to meet the needs of employers in local areas. We are also investing £80m in National Colleges to meet higher level skills gaps in sectors critical to the economy.</p><p>Taken together, this will help to ensure that people are equipped with the higher level skills that employers need to be globally competitive and drive productivity.</p><p>We continue to invest in learning opportunities for those with a disadvantage or learning difficulty who need additional support, enabling tailored programmes to be made available to help those furthest from learning or the workplace. This is through the AEB which can be used to provide the skills and learning disadvantaged adults need to equip them for work, an apprenticeship or further learning. It supports Community Learning which helps adults of different ages and backgrounds to develop their skills, self-confidence, motivation and resilience in order to improve their wellbeing and progress towards formal learning and employment. Funding is also available to help adult learners (19+) overcome barriers which prevent them from taking part in learning. This includes help to meet the additional needs of learners with learning difficulties and/or disabilities.</p><p>The national Community Learning Mental Health Study (2015/17) is a £20m 2-year research project funded through the 2014 Autumn Statement, which will help us to assess the effect of adult education on improving mental health and employment and social isolation outcomes. The findings will be available in January 2018.</p><p>In addition, the Department has already commissioned the Learning and Work Institute to engage in work with adult education providers to explore and better understand which social metrics may help us better assess social outcomes (like improving social connectedness) through non-formal learning. Learning and Work Institute is due to report on the first year of this work in March 2017.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","61135","2017-01-27T13:30:36.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677641/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677641/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-23","Adult Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the number of adults achieving Level 4 qualifications or above and (a) the ability of unemployed adults to obtain employment and (b) her Department's progress in tackling the skills and productivity gap.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","61137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677642","Department for Education","false","2017-02-07","<p>As part of the Government’s work on lifetime learning, we have identified significant trends such as a decline in work-based training, and key barriers deterring adults from gaining new skills, including perceived costs and prevailing attitudes about the benefits of learning. As set out in the Industrial Strategy Green Paper, the Government is committed to exploring ambitious new approaches to tackle these barriers and encourage lifetime learning, including reaching out to workers whose industries are rapidly changing or in decline.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-02-07T14:08:06.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677642/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677642/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-23","Adult Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Government's Post-16 Skills Plan, published in July 2016, when her Department plans to publish its approach to lifetime learning for adults; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","61138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677643","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-26","<p>The UK Space Agency is working closely with businesses to understand their concerns and working with colleagues across Government to make sure we understand all of the potential risks and opportunities across the economy. This will continue to inform our approach as we seek to shape our future relationship with Europe.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-26T17:22:33.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677643/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677643/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Space Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions officials from the UK Space Agency have had since June 2016 with (a) his Department, (b) the Ministry of Defence, (c) the Department for Exiting the European Union and (d) the Department for International Trade on access to space programmes initiated by the European Space Agency and funded by EU programmes.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","61117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677644","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-26","<p>The use of Border Adjustment Mechanisms in the EU Emissions Trading System (ETS) could potentially have a number of serious negative effects on the world trade system. For this reason, the Government supports the provision of free allowances as the best way to protect industries from the risk of carbon leakage.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-26T11:23:27.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677644/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677644/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Lime: EU Emissions Trading Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the border adjustment mechanism proposed by the European Parliament ENVI Committee for the EU Emissions Trading Scheme on lime manufacturers in the UK.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","61110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677645","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-31","<p>The decision to close the BIS Sheffield office was confirmed by the former BIS Board in May 2016 and plans have been implemented to a large extent. BEIS remains committed to honouring the full package of support offered to the small remaining number of affected staff.</p><p> </p><p>BEIS has held constructive dialogue with the trade unions regarding the remaining staff and continues to work closely with OGDs to explore opportunities for redeployment.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-31T10:34:14.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677645/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677645/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Corrected Answer of 16 January 2017 to Question 43632, what decision his Department has made on the future role of his Department's Sheffield office at St Paul's Place.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","61104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677646","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-26","<p>The Government understands the important role post offices play in communities across the country, especially in the more remote, rural areas. This is why in our manifesto we committed to secure the future of 3,000 rural post offices.</p><p> </p><p>Thanks to Government investment the UK’s network of 11,600 branches is at its most stable in decades, with over 98% of the UK population in rural areas within 3 miles of a post office. The investment is offering real improvements to customers, including an extra 200,000 opening hours every week and over 4,200 post offices open on a Sunday.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s recent consultation will help us understand what the public and businesses expect from the Post Office and to understand more fully what subsidy is needed and what it should be used for.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-26T14:18:56.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677646/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677646/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Post Offices: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of progress in securing the future of rural post offices; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","61093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677647","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-31","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy works closely with the Department for Education (DfE) which is responsible for skills policy and also the Construction Industry Training Board (CITB), the body that supports training and skills in construction.</p><p> </p><p>DfE is currently working with employers in the construction industry to develop new apprenticeships for the sector. While evidence suggests there are sufficient learners going through the skills system, with over 200,000 construction qualifications being taken each year, reforms set out in the skills plan (July 2016) will ensure these qualifications become more relevant and meet the industry’s needs.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Construction Leadership Council, the business led sector council which advises Government on key strategic issues, has investigated the labour model in their construction and commissioned an independent report from Mark Farmer ( published in October 2016, <a href="http://www.cast-consultancy.com/news-casts/farmer-review-uk-construction-labour-model-3/" target="_blank">http://www.cast-consultancy.com/news-casts/farmer-review-uk-construction-labour-model-3)</a> making recommendations for industry and Government. Both the Government and the Construction Leadership Council is currently considering the review’s recommendations.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-01-31T15:04:18.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677647/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677647/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Construction: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans the Government has to tackle future skills shortages in the construction industry.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","61184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677648","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-31","<p>The Government continues to monitor the potential impacts that leaving the EU may have on the availability of skilled workers. We cannot speculate on the outcome of Brexit negotiations, but the Government has made it clear that the UK remains open to the talent we need from Europe and the rest of the world.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education (DfE) is currently working closely with employers in the construction industry to develop new apprenticeships for the sector. While evidence suggests there are sufficient learners going through the skills system, with over 200,000 construction qualifications being taken each year, reforms set out in the skills plan (July 2016) will ensure these qualifications become more relevant and meet the industry’s needs.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-01-31T15:01:11.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677648/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677648/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-23","Construction: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the availability of skilled construction workers.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","61185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677649","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-26","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) will detail our total spend in the annual reports and accounts.</p><p>As of 12 January 2017, DIT headcount is 2,841.</p><p>DIT is in the process of establishing budgets for the next four years and these will be provided to Parliament, in the supplementary estimates, later this financial year.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-26T17:46:29.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677649/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677649/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-23","Department for International Trade: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, (a) how much his Department cost to set up, (b) how many staff his Department employs and (c) what the estimated cost of running the Department is for the next three years.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","61139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677650","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-26","<p>a) Costs of setting up dept<br><br>The total expenditure of the Department for Exiting the European Union will be set out in the Annual Report and Accounts at the end of the financial year as is standard practice.<br><br>b) Number of staff <br><br>The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 300 staff, plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels from the UK Permanent Representation to the EU, and is growing fast.<br><br>c) Cost of running dept for next three years <br><br>The Autumn Statement announced additional funding of up to £51m in 2016-17 and up to £94m per year from 2017-18 until the UK’s exit is complete. The full budget for the department will be presented to Parliament at the Supplementary Estimate as is standard practi<strong>ce.</strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-26T17:34:29.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677650/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677650/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-23","Department for Exiting the European Union: Costs and Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, (a) how much his Department cost to set up, (b) how many staff his Department employs and (c) what the estimated cost of running the Department is for the next three years.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","61140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677651","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-26","<p>The Prime Minister is clear that we will continue to work with our European partners on defence and security policy. European leaders have welcomed this commitment. This is the right approach: working closely on defence and security with our closest geographical partners makes our citizens safer. The Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union has regular discussions with Ministerial colleagues on this issue.<br><br></p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-26T17:31:57.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677651/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677651/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-23","Defence and Security: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions officials from his Department have had with (a) the Department for International Trade and (b) the Ministry of Defence on (i) access to and (ii) influence in collaborative defence and security programmes run by the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","61118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677652","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>As the Department responsible for Enterprise Zones and the Government’s lead on the Midlands Engine, we consider Enterprise Zones and Food Enterprise Zones to have an important role in stimulating growth in our rural economy, attracting investment and jobs to the Midlands Engine area.</p><p>Two Enterprise Zones in predominantly rural areas of the Midlands Engine have helped to attract businesses and new investment from around the world. Five Food Enterprise Zones in Greater Lincolnshire, Melton and Wychavon will be working to attract investment and encourage greater collaboration between British food and farming businesses.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-01-30T17:29:04.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677652/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677652/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-23","Enterprise Zones: Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions his Department has had with the Department for Communities and Local Government on the role of rural enterprise zones in the Midlands growth engine.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","61085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677653","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-27","<p>DCLG leads on integration and cohesion and is involved in many fora with communities affected by intolerant attitudes within in the UK. My department works with DCLG on a wide range of issues, including community cohesion. The Cross-Government Hate Crime Programme brings together officials, criminal justice agencies, victims and communities and has maintained oversight of hate crime during 2016 to ensure responses have been swift and effective.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-27T12:00:36.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677653/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677653/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-23","Community Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent discussions his Department has had with the Home Office on promotion of tolerance and respect for all communities.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","61086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677654","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has used the services of a number of consultancy firms to support departmental set-up and planning. The cost to the public purse on each occasion was either nil, a nominal fee or at the same rate as a civil service salary. <br><br></p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-30T17:08:59.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677654/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677654/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-23","Department for Exiting the European Union: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the total value is of contracts let between his Department and consultants has been since the establishment of that Department.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","61142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677655","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-27","<p>The Department is continuing to use the services of six external secondees from consulting firms that were working for the department on 30 November.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-27T13:47:28.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677655/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677655/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-23","Department for Exiting the European Union: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the number of employees of consultants retained by his Department who were working for the Department on 30 November 2016.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","61168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678795","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-26","<p>The Prime Minister was clear in her speech that she wants to guarantee the status of EU citizens already in Britain, and our nationals in the EU, as early as she can. She told other EU leaders that we could give people the certainty they want straight away, and reach such a deal now. Resolving this challenge as soon as possible is the right and fair thing to do. Other EU leaders recognise the importance of reaching a reciprocal deal. This includes the Polish Prime Minister Szydlo who discussed this with the Prime Minister in November.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-26T17:34:55.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678795/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678795/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678795/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-23","EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what priority he plans to accord to the future status of EU nationals in the UK during negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","908407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678949","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-26","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union, working with officials across government, continues to undertake a wide range of data analysis covering the entirety of the UK economy and our trading relationships with the EU. We are looking at over 50 sectors as well as cross-cutting regulatory issues. This will inform the UK's position for the upcoming negotiations with our EU partners. We want to ensure that British businesses have the maximum freedom to trade with and operate within European markets – and to let European businesses do the same in Britain.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-01-26T17:13:40.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678949/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678949/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-23","Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on businesses in (a) the UK and (b) the EU.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sheryll Murray","South East Cornwall","Mrs Sheryll Murray","908412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/676002","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-25","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), which is operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>The questions have been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the Honourable gentleman by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","60983 ; 60984 ; 60985 ; 60986","2017-01-25T10:13:08.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/676002/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/676002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/676002/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-20","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many commercial debt management companies have applied for a licence but have been declined by the Financial Conduct Authority in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","60987"
